    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nCalling `nvim_parse_cmd()` with a command line string that only contains range (`:h :command-range`) or command modifier (`:h :command-modifiers`) throws an error.\n\nAccording to the documentation it should \"Parse command line\". Having only range is a valid command line text: pressing `<CR>` will go to the target line. Same for command modifiers: pressing `<CR>` usually just does nothing (except `:hide`).\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n1. `nvim --clean`\n2. Try calling `nvim_parse_cmd()` with only range. Any of the following throws `E5108: Lua: [string \":lua\"]:1: Parsing command-line`:\n    2.1.  `:=vim.api.nvim_parse_cmd('1', {})`\n    2.2.  `:=vim.api.nvim_parse_cmd(\"'<,'>\", {})` (after having visually selected something in a buffer).\n    2.3.  `:=vim.api.nvim_parse_cmd(\"aboveleft\", {})`\n\n### Expected behavior\n\n`nvim_parse_cmd()` succeeds to parse command line text containing only range or command modifier. The output should contain `cmd = ''` plus valid `range` or `mods` entry.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.12.0-dev-1664+ge0308dc147\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nNo, doesn't have this functionality\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nEndeavourOS Linux x86_64, 6.17.8-arch1-1\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nGhostty 1.2.3-arch2\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-ghostty\n\n### Installation\n\nAppimage",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
